Why version control

  • You will forget things
  • Version control logs every step
  • Backups with history
  • Easier collaboration
  • Dropbox is not sufficient!!

Version control with git

  • git: the stupid content tracker
  • Git is stupid. But it replaced worse systems, so we use it
    • There are better systems now, but we're stuck with it
  • Git is best with small text-only files – it doesn't like huge PDF docs
  • Porcelain vs plumbing - We will only work with porcelain commands but be aware that there is a lot of ugly plumbing going on

Some Git plumbing…

What is a repository, really?

A series of commit objects with attached metadata that point to each other.

Branching

What is a branch? Simply a pointer for the 'current' commit in a sequence of ongoing commits:

Your "main" branch is always called master. What if you make a new branch called testing?

There can be many branches around at the same time. Where you are right now, your "working directory", is a special pointer called HEAD.

Here there are two branches, master and testing, and testing is the current active branch since that is what HEAD points to.

Once new commits are made on a branch, HEAD and the branch label move with the new commits:

If we continue to work on both branches, the history could diverge:

Git uses the common ancestor to compute the necessary information to merge the diverging branches back together.

When to use branching

  • Always.
  • Never work directly on master
  • master should contain your "known good" code, writing, etc.

Collaboration workflow

  • Fork a Github repository (this creates a personal copy of their repository)

  • Clone it in the desktop app

  • Make changes on a branch

  • Sync commits

  • Open pull request (on the website)
